\title{Thread Border Router Catalogue: Transport Mesh for the BCI Factory}
\author{bmorphism}
\import{macros}
\date{2026-04-03}
\taxon{definition}

\p{The BCI Factory pipeline ([[horse-0001]]) requires a \strong{transport mesh} connecting 6 device modalities at 50Hz. Thread (IEEE 802.15.4) provides the low-latency, IPv6-native, self-healing mesh. A \strong{Thread Border Router} (TBR) bridges the 802.15.4 mesh to IP networks — it is the sheaf's restriction map realized in silicon.}

\p{Categorically: the TBR is a \strong{cocontinuous functor} ##{\mathrm{TBR}: \mathbf{ThreadMesh} \to \mathbf{IP}} preserving the colimit (mesh topology) while embedding it into the ambient IP network. The BCI pipeline's signal presheaf ([[horse-0002]]) factors through this transport layer.}

\subtree{
\title{GF(3) Transport Trit}

\p{Each TBR is classified by its transport trit:}
\table{
  \tr{\th{Trit} \th{Class} \th{Meaning}}
  \tr{\td{+1} \td{Hub-primary} \td{Full smart home hub with TBR (Apple HomePod, Google Nest, SmartThings)}}
  \tr{\td{-1} \td{Mesh-native} \td{Purpose-built radio (SiLabs dev kit, Nordic DK, USB dongle)}}
  \tr{\td{0} \td{Router-embedded} \td{TBR integrated into Wi-Fi mesh (eero, Deco, Nest Wifi)}}
}

\p{Conservation: hub(+1) + mesh(-1) + router(0) = 0. The transport layer mirrors the BCI rooms: bci.red(+1), bci.blue(-1), bci.place(0).}
}

