\subtree{
\title{BCI Factory Transport Architecture}

\p{The 222 Dore deployment ([[horse-0001]]) uses \strong{Apple HomePod} as canonical TBR hub — it is the \strong{descent functor} for the transport layer, gluing the Thread mesh into the IP backbone where the pipeline runs.}

\table{
  \tr{\th{BCI Device} \th{Transport} \th{Thread Role} \th{Pipeline Stage}}
  \tr{\td{OpenBCI Cyton 8ch} \td{BLE → Thread (via nRF5340)} \td{Sleepy End Device} \td{Stage 1 ([[horse-0002]])}}
  \tr{\td{fNIRS dual-wavelength} \td{Thread native} \td{Router} \td{Stage 2 ([[horse-0003]])}}
  \tr{\td{Vibrotactile haptic} \td{Thread native} \td{End Device} \td{Feedback loop}}
  \tr{\td{sEMG surface} \td{BLE → Thread} \td{Sleepy End Device} \td{Stage 1}}
  \tr{\td{Eye tracker 120Hz} \td{USB (latency-critical)} \td{N/A} \td{Stage 4 ([[horse-0005]])}}
  \tr{\td{Braille display} \td{Thread native} \td{End Device} \td{Output}}
  \tr{\td{VARMBLIXT lamp} \td{Matter over Thread} \td{End Device} \td{Ambient feedback}}
  \tr{\td{HomePod} \td{Wi-Fi + Thread} \td{\strong{Border Router}} \td{Transport descent}}
}

\p{The eye tracker stays USB — 120Hz is beyond Thread's comfortable latency envelope. Everything else meshes. The HomePod TBR provides the cocontinuous functor from device mesh to pipeline IP.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Trit Census}

\p{Of the 69 TBRs:}
\table{
  \tr{\th{Trit} \th{Count} \th{Class}}
  \tr{\td{+1} \td{30} \td{Hub-primary (Apple, Google, Amazon, Samsung, IKEA, Aqara, Hue, HA hubs)}}
  \tr{\td{-1} \td{19} \td{Mesh-native (SiLabs, Nordic, ESP32, USB dongles)}}
  \tr{\td{0} \td{20} \td{Router-embedded (Nanoleaf, routers, industrial)}}
}

\p{30 + 19 + 20 = 69. Trit sum: 30(+1) + 19(-1) + 20(0) = 30 - 19 = 11 ≡ 2 (mod 3). \strong{Not conserved} at the raw device level — the market favors hubs. But within the BCI Factory deployment, we select one from each class: HomePod(+1) + nRF5340(-1) + VARMBLIXT-via-Thread(0) = 0. \strong{Conserved at the deployment level.}}
}

\subtree{
\title{Connection to Stacks Project}

\p{The TBR catalogue connects to the Stacks Project via:}
\ol{
  \li{\strong{Sites} (Tag 00VH): The Thread mesh topology IS a Grothendieck site — devices are objects, radio links are covering morphisms}
  \li{\strong{Descent} (Tag 0238): The TBR performs descent — gluing local device sections into a global IP-accessible state}
  \li{\strong{Étale morphisms} (Tag 03N1): Thread's peer-to-peer mesh links are étale — local isomorphisms between neighbor devices}
  \li{\strong{Stacks} (Tag 026K): The full BCI pipeline with re-referencing gauge symmetry IS a stack over the Thread site}
}

\p{See [[xref-0001]] for the complete Stacks Project cross-reference.}
}
